_date         = \n| government_type          = \n| government_footnotes     = \n| leader_title             = Mayor\n| leader_name              = Rochelle Robinson\n| leader_title1            = City Manager\n| leader_name1             = Marcia Hampton\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_13.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E9\n| area_total_km2           = 58.70\n| area_land_km2            = 58.42\n| area_water_km2           = 0.28\n| area_water_percent       = \n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = 366\n| elevation_ft             = 1201\n| population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n| population_total         = 30961\n| population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n| population_est           = 34190\n| pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n| population_density_km2   = 585.22\n<!--2018 pop estimate-->\n| population_density_sq_mi = 1515.72\n<!-- General information ---------------->\n| timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset               = -5\n| timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = -4\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n| postal_code              = 30122, 30133-30135. 30154\n| area_code                = [[Area code 770|770]]/[[Area codes 678 and 470|678/470]]\n| blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info               = 13-23900<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref>\n| blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info              = 0355535<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n| website                  = {{URL|www.douglasvillega.gov}}\n|area_total_sq_mi = 22.66\n|area_land_sq_mi = 22.56\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.11\n}}\n[[File:USA-Georgia-Douglasville County Courthouse.jpg|thumb|250px|Douglas County Courthouse]]\n\nThe city of '''Douglasville''' is the [[county seat]] of [[Douglas County, Georgia|Douglas County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States. {{As of|2010|alt=As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]}}, the city had a population of 30,961,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US1323900| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Douglasville city, Georgia| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=October 23, 2015}}{{dead link|bot=medic|date=April 2020}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> up from 20,065 in 2000.\n\nDouglasville is located approximately {{convert|20|mi}} west of [[Atlanta]] and is part of the [[Atlanta metropolitan area|Atlanta Metro Area]]. Highway access can be obtained via three interchanges along [[Interstate 20]].\n\n==History==\nLocated along a natural rise in the topography, Douglasville was originally known as \"Skint Chestnut.\"<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.kenkrakow.com/gpn/d.pdf | title=Georgia Place-Names: Their History and Origins | publisher=Winship Press | author=Krakow, Kenneth K. | year=1975 | location=Macon, GA | page=64 | isbn=0-915430-00-2}}</ref> The name was derived from a large tree used by Native Americans as a landmark; it was stripped of its bark so as to be more conspicuous.\n\nDouglasville was founded in 1874 as the railroad was constructed in the area. That same year, Douglasville was designated as the county seat of the recently formed Douglas County. The community was named for Senator [[Stephen A. Douglas]] of Illinois.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=REtEXQNWq6MC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA228#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Historical Gazetteer of the United States | publisher=Routledge | date=May 13, 2013 | accessdate=30 November 2013 | author=Hellmann, Paul T. | page=228}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgia General Assembly]] first incorporated Douglasville in 1875.<ref>{{cite book|title=Acts Passed by the General Assembly of Georgia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qRY4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA162|year=1875|publisher=J. Johnston|page=162}}</ref>\n\nIn 1916, the Reverend Atkinson of Douglasville was a key figure in the [[Arc Light Controversy]] in Atlanta.\n\nOn September 21, 2009, Douglas County was devastated by the worst flood in Georgia history. Over {{convert|18|in|mm|0}} of rain fell in one night, destroying many roads and homes. The county was later declared a disaster area, and the governor of Georgia declared a state of emergency. The flooding most affected the areas of Douglasville, [[Villa Rica, Georgia|Villa Rica]], [[Austell, Georgia|Austell]], [[Lithia Springs, Georgia|Lithia Springs]], and [[Chapel Hill, Georgia|Chapel Hill]]. The disaster killed more than eight people in the county, most of them in the Douglasville area.\n\n==Geography==\nDouglasville is located in north-central Douglas County at {{Coord|33|44|59|N|84|43|23|W|type:city|display=inline,title}} (33.749824, \u221284.723190). Lithia Springs is {{convert|6|mi|0}} to the northeast along [[U.S. Route 78]], and Villa Rica is {{convert|10|mi|0}} to the west. [[Hiram, Georgia|Hiram]] is {{convert|9|mi|0}} to the north via [[Georgia State Route 92|SR 92]]. [[Interstate 20 in Georgia|Interstate 20]] passes south of downtown, leading east {{convert|22|mi}} to downtown [[Atlanta]] and west {{convert|125|mi}} to [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Alabama]]. I-20 provides access to the city from exits 34, 36, and 37.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], Douglasville has a total area of {{convert|58.5|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|58.2|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.3|km2|order=flip|1}}, or 0.58%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\nDouglasville has an elevation of {{convert|1209|ft|m|abbr=on}} above sea level.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 286\n|1890= 863\n|1900= 1140\n|1910= 1462\n|1920= 2159\n|1930= 2316\n|1940= 2555\n|1950= 3400\n|1960= 4462\n|1970= 5472\n|1980= 7641\n|1990= 11635\n|2000= 20065\n|2010= 30961\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=34190\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|df=mdy}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 Census===\nAs of the census of 2010, there were 30,961 people, 11,627 households, and 7,692 families residing in the city. The population density was 1,376 people per square mile (532.0/km\u00b2). There were 13,163 housing units at an average density of 585.0 per square mile (226.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 55.9% African American, 36.0% White (33.4% Non-Hispanic White), 0.2% Native American, 1.8% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 3.3% from other races, and 2.8% from two or more races. 7.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.\n\nThere were 11,627 households out of which 36.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 39.3% were married couples living together, 21.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.8% were non-families. 28.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.58 and the average family size was 3.18.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 28.3% under the age of 18, 9.5% from 18 to 24, 33.2% from 25 to 44, 22.2% from 45 to 64, and 6.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 32.7 years. For every 100 females, there were 87.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 83.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city is $47,596, and the median income for a family was $54,375. Males had a median income of $45,933 versus $39,675 for females. The per capita income for the city was $26,002. 15.9% of the population and 14.1% of families were below the poverty line. Out of the total population, 22.2% of those under the age of 18 and 15.1% of those 65 and older are living below the poverty line.<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\" />\n\n===2000 Census===\nAs of the census of 2000, there were 20,065 people, 7,286 households, and 5,078 families residing in the city. The population density was 938.5 people per square mile (362.4/km\u00b2). There were 7,903 housing units at an average density of 369.6 per square mile (142.7/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 63.84% White, 30.29% African American, 0.31% Native American, 1.73% Asian, 0.01% Pacific Islander, 1.69% from other races, and 2.13% from two or more races. 3.99% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.\n\nThere were 7,286 households out of which 38.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.2% were married couples living together, 16.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 30.3% were non-families. 22.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.68 and the average family size was 3.16.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 28.3% under the age of 18, 11.1% from 18 to 24, 34.4% from 25 to 44, 19.6% from 45 to 64, and 6.6% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 31 years. For every 100 females, there were 94.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city is $45,289, and the median income for a family was $52,340. Males had a median income of $37,464 versus $27,038 for females. The per capita income for the city was $22,283. 12.2% of the population and 10.1% of families were below the poverty line. Out of the total population, 17.3% of those under the age of 18 and 8.1% of those 65 and older are living below the poverty line.<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\" />\n\n==Economy==\nThe historic Downtown hosts none of the shops and eateries. A vibrant business area in Douglasville is located north of the city between Chapel Hill Road and [[Georgia State Route 5]], around the Douglas Boulevard Corridor. [[Arbor Place Mall]] is located in this area, as are many major retail stores and fast food chains.\n\nThe Fairburn Road area also hosts many shops, food stores and fast food spots. Some vacated to make way for an expansion of the highway in early 2008. Expansion is aided by the [[#Douglasville Development Authority|Douglasville Development Authority]] (described below).\n\nIn recent years, the historic downtown district and surrounding areas have become favorite backdrops for the film industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitdouglasville.com/index.aspx?NID=97|title=Film Production|publisher=}}</ref> Productions include [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things]]'' (2016), ''[[The Founder (film)|The Founder]]'' (2015), ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1|Mocking Jay]]'' Part 1 (2014), ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire|Catching Fire]]'' (2013), ''[[Finding Carter]]'' (MTV series 2014), and ''[[Kill the Messenger (2014 film)|Kill the Messenger]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.developdouglas.com/filmtv|title=Welcome to the Film Office {{!}} Douglas County|website=www.developdouglas.com|access-date=2016-12-13}}</ref>\n\n===Top employers===\nAccording to Douglasville's 2011 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.douglasville.ga.us/DocumentCenter/Home/View/2073|title=City of Douglasville CAFR|publisher=}}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of employees\n|-\n|1\n| [[Walmart]]\n|750\n|-\n|2\n| [[Kroger]]\n|487\n|-\n|3\n| [[American Red Cross]]\n|450\n|-\n|4\n| Benton-Georgia\n|300\n|-\n|5\n| [[Sam's Club]]\n|180\n|-\n|6\n| [[The Home Depot]]\n|155\n|-\n|7\n| A.L.P. Lighting Components\n|120\n|-\n|8\n| [[Medline Industries|Medline]]\n|111\n|-\n|9\n| G & L Marble\n|96\n|-\n|10\n| Reflek Manufacturing\n|75\n|}\n\nThe Douglasville CAFR table of principal employers (p.&nbsp;77) does not show public employees.  The Douglas County School System currently employs over 3,550 people, including teachers, administrators, and support staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.douglas.k12.ga.us/|title=Douglas County School System|first=Douglas County School|last=System|website=www.douglas.k12.ga.us}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n\n===Points of interest===\n[[File:Basket Creek Cemetery - White Section.jpg|thumb|Photo of the White section of the [[Basket Creek Cemetery]], including Civil War soldiers' graves and one [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] grave (several rocks are piled on top located in the back)]]\n\nThe Central Business District of downtown Douglasville is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] as a historic district; it is an outstanding example of a turn-of-the-century southern railroad town. The majority of the buildings are one- and two-story brick structures dating from the mid-19th century into the mid-20th century. Most are of Victorian-era commercial design set flush with the sidewalk. The buildings' styles include Romanesque, Italianate, and Queen Anne. Many of the doorways and windows have Gothic arched openings and hooded windows. The dominant landscape feature is the railroad right-of-way running east-to-west through downtown.\n\nIn the center of town is a small plaza, which was converted from a street block, known as O'Neal Plaza (named after the former O'Neal's department store, now used as the Douglasville City Hall). The plaza features a small performance venue and concrete fountain. It is home to many festivals year round. This is the site of the annual Christmas Tree Lighting Festival.\n\n* The Douglasville Convention & Visitors Bureau<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitdouglasville.com/|title=Douglasville CVB, GA - Official Website - Official Website|website=www.visitdouglasville.com}}</ref> is located in the heart of downtown and serves as the city's welcome center.\n* The Douglas County Cultural Arts Center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsdouglas.org/|title=Home Page - Cultural Arts Council Douglasville/Douglas County|website=Cultural Arts Council Douglasville/Douglas County}}</ref> is located at Campbellton Street, south of Downtown. The center holds art shows and special events throughout the year, and hosts events for schools across the county. Classes for a variety of visual and performing arts are available year-round for all ages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsdouglas.org/index.htm|title=Welcome to the Cultural Arts Council of Douglasville & Douglas County|website=www.artsdouglas.org|access-date=2016-12-13}}</ref>\n* The courthouse on Hospital Drive hosts the Douglasville Farmers and Artisans Market <!--Sadly, the official name of this festival contains no apostrophes; I looked it up. --> every Wednesday from 4 pm until 7 pm, from April until November. \n* The Douglasville Downtown Conference Center is located at 6701 Church Street. It hosts corporate meetings, community events, and social gatherings. Summit Church of West Georgia meets here on Sunday mornings. The {{convert|37000|sqft|adj=on}} conference center, with a two-level, 300-space parking deck, opened in early 2013. It has a {{convert|7600|ft|adj=on}} ballroom space that can be divided into five rooms. It includes a 150-seat auditorium, a 15-person boardroom, a business center, three meeting rooms, two pre-function spaces, bride and groom dressing rooms, and a terrace in the back. \n* The Douglas County Museum of History and Art<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratedouglascounty.com/view/programs/view_prog/&cdept=185&department=douglas+county+museum+of+history+and+art|title=Douglas County, Georgia USA|website=www.celebratedouglascounty.com}}</ref> on West Broad Street is housed in the [[Douglas County Courthouse (Douglasville, Georgia)|county's historic 1956 courthouse]], which has been preserved for its unique architecture and is listed in the National Register for Historic Places. The museum features an exhibit of county history as well as seasonal displays. \n* [[Arbor Place Mall]] is home to over 100 shops and restaurants. The anchor stores are Dillard's, Sears-closing this February, Macy's, Belk, J.C. Penney, Old Navy and Bed Bath & Beyond. The mall sponsors many festivals, as well as Douglasville's July 4 celebrations.\n* Champ's Clock Shop and Museum's<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.champsclock.com/|title=Welcome to Champs Clock Shop - Near: Atlanta, Marietta, Newnan, Carrollton, Duluth, Clocks, Annsiston, Alabama, Georgia|website=www.champsclock.com}}</ref> attractions include the world's largest real cuckoo clock.\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n* Hunter Park is Douglasville's largest park, and is home to the county [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Club]]. Many festivals, sports activities, and recreational activities take place here. The park features a playground, wildlife pond and trail, seven tennis courts, 11 baseball/softball fields, including one designed for the handicapped, and an 18-hole [[disc golf]] course that opened in 2015. The small train for children that operated during the summer no longer exists. The park is named after the late 1st Lt. \"Jerry\" Hunter (USAF), Douglas County's first casualty of the [[Vietnam War]].\n* Boundary Waters Park, located on GA Highway 92 North/Highway 166 East, has several pools which are open to the public. The Boundary Waters Aquatic Center <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratedouglascounty.com/view/departments/view_dept/&cdept=195&department=Boundary+Waters+Aquatic+Center|title=Douglas County, Georgia USA|website=www.celebratedouglascounty.com}}</ref> features an eight-lane, 25-yard heated competition pool and a four-lane, heated therapeutic/teaching pool. The center is home to the Douglas County Stingrays<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamunify.com/Home.jsp?team=gsdcs|title=Douglas County Stingrays :|website=www.teamunify.com}}</ref> swim team as well as local high school and Special Olympics swim teams. The park complex includes an array of ball fields, walking and horseriding trails,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratedouglascounty.com/view/global/viewdownload/&docid=5548&file=/Boundary_Waters_Trail_Map_Includes_Greenway_1-8-15.pdf |title=Map |website=www.celebratedouglascounty.com |format=PDF}}</ref> and an 18-hole disc golf course<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratedouglascounty.com/view/global/viewdownload/&docid=3635&file=/brochure_of_disc_golf.pdf |title=Brochure |website=www.celebratedouglascounty.com |format=PDF}}</ref> \n* Deer Lick Park<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratedouglascounty.com/view/departments/view_dept/&cdept=207&department=Deer+Lick+Park|title=Douglas County, Georgia USA|website=www.celebratedouglascounty.com}}</ref> is located approximately {{convert|3|mi|0}} south of Interstate 20 and east of the city limits on Mack Road. This 66-acre park features softball fields, a sand volleyball court, an 18-hole disc golf course, tennis courts, a gymnasium, and batting cages. It also hosts a three-acre fishing lake with a pier, playground, an amphitheater, gazebo, group shelters, and restroom facilities.\n* The West Pines Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westpinesgc.com/|title=West Pines Golf Club - Douglasville, GA \u2013 Welcome to West Pines Golf Club!|website=www.westpinesgc.com}}</ref> was purchased by the city in 2003 and is now operated as a public course.\n* The Fowler Field Soccer Complex<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.douglasville.ga.us/115/Fowler-Field-Park|title=Fowler Field Park - Douglasville, GA - Official Website|website=www.ci.douglasville.ga.us}}</ref> is located in the southwest part of the city, on Chapel Hill Road.\n* The Chestnut Log Soccer Complex is located on Pope Road beside Chestnut Log Middle School, about \u00bd mile west of SR 92 (Fairburn Road).\n* Jesse Davis Park is located north of downtown Douglasville and serves as a neighborhood park for residents of North Douglasville. The park was recently renovated, and has a playground and a community swimming pool.\n* [[Sweetwater Creek State Park]] is a {{convert|2549|acre|km2|adj=on}} park {{convert|7|mi|0}} east of Douglasville. The park has {{convert|9|mi|0}} of wooded trails that follow the stream to the ruins of the New Manchester Manufacturing Company, a textile mill burned during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. The park has a {{convert|215|acre|km2|adj=on}} lake with two fishing docks, canoe and fishing boat rentals, 11 picnic shelters, playground, visitors center and museum.\n* Clinton Nature Preserve<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratedouglascounty.com/view/departments/view_dept/&cdept=211&department=Clinton+Nature+Preserve|title=Douglas County, Georgia USA|website=www.celebratedouglascounty.com}}</ref> located {{convert|7|mi|0}} west of Douglasville, is a 200-acre historical preserve, located off the Post Road exit of Interstate 20, which features a pre-Civil War log cabin, picnic areas, walking and mountain biking trails, a gravel walking track, fishing, an outdoor amphitheatre, and a 100-percent disabled-accessible children's play garden.\n\n==Government==\nIn 2015, the city elected [[Rochelle Robinson]] as its first female and first African American mayor.<ref name=\"pratt\">[http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2016/2/16/black-mayors-georgia-towns.html Timothy Pratt, \"New black mayors make a difference, one Georgia town at a time\"], ''Aljazeera'' (US), 16 February 2016; accessed 12 December 2016</ref>\n\nThe City Council is elected from [[single-member district]]s.\n\n===Law enforcement===\nThe Douglasville police chief is Gary Sparks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.douglasville.ga.us/17/Police|title=Douglasville Police Department {{!}} Douglasville, GA - Official Website|website=www.ci.douglasville.ga.us|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> The Douglasville Police Department is located at 2083 Fairburn Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.douglasville.ga.us/|title=Douglasville, GA - Official Website - Official Website|website=www.ci.douglasville.ga.us|access-date=July 26, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716042903/http://ci.douglasville.ga.us/|archive-date=July 16, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> The sheriff is Tim Pounds, and the Douglas County Sheriff's Office is located at 8470 Earl D Lee Boulevard in Douglasville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheriff.douglas.ga.us/|title=Home|first=Douglas County Sheriff's|last=Office|website=Douglas County Sheriff's Office (GA)}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nEducation in Douglasville is varied, with a large public school system<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.douglas.k12.ga.us/ |title=Douglas County School District |publisher=Douglas.k12.ga.us |date=November 7, 2011 |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref> and many private schools. The [[Douglas County School District]] operates 21 elementary schools, eight middle schools, and five high schools, covering grades pre-K to 12th grade.<ref>[http://www.doe.k12.ga.us/ReportingFW.aspx?PageReq=111&PID=62&PTID=69&CountyId=648&T=0&FY=2009 Georgia Board of Education]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved July 30, 2010.</ref>\n\nDouglasville hosts a campus (\"instructional site\") of [[Georgia Highlands College]]. Nearby universities and colleges include Strayer College,<ref name=\"strayer1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.strayer.edu/ |title=Strayer University |publisher=Strayer.edu |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref> West Georgia Technical College,<ref name=\"westgatech1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westgatech.edu/ |title=West Georgia Technical College |publisher=Westgatech.edu |date=September 20, 2010 |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref> and Mercer University.<ref name=\"mercer1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mercer.edu/ |title=Mercer University |publisher=Mercer.edu |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDouglasville has numerous secular and religious private schools, including:\n\n* Harvester Christian Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harvesteracademy.com/ |title=Harvester Christian Academy |publisher=Harvesteracademy.com |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* Heirway Christian Academy<ref name=\"heirwaychristianacademy1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.heirwaychristianacademy.com/joomla/ |title=Heirway Christian Academy |publisher=Heirway Christian Academy |accessdate=November 13, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112161137/http://www.heirwaychristianacademy.com/joomla/ |archive-date=November 12, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*The International Montessori Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theinternationalmontessoriacademy.com/ |title=The International Montessori Academy |publisher=The International Montessori Academy |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* The Kings Way Christian School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kwcsinfo.com/ |title=The Kings Way Christian School |publisher=Kwcsinfo.com |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* Primrose School at Brookmont<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primroseschools.com/OurSchools/Georgia/Atlanta/Douglasville/Brookmont |title=Primrose School at Brookmont |publisher=Primroseschools.com |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* Saint Rose Academy<ref name=\"saintroseacademy1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.saintroseacademy.net/ |title=St. Rose Academy |publisher=Saintroseacademy.net |date=September 29, 2004 |accessdate=November 13, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326194214/http://www.saintroseacademy.net/ |archive-date=March 26, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Sunbrook Academy at Chapel Hill<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunbrookacademy.com/chapel-hill-douglasville-ga/|title=Preschool in Douglasville, Georgia - Sunbrook Academy in Douglasville|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Chapelhill Christian School <ref>{{cite web|url=http://cchschool.com/ |title=Chapel Hill Christian School &#124; Official Home of Chapel Hill Christian School |publisher=Cchschool.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-12}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nDouglasville is served by the ''Douglas County Sentinel'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.douglascountysentinel.com/|title=douglascountysentinel.com - Local.News.First|first=Douglas County|last=Sentinel|website=Douglas County Sentinel}}</ref> a three-day-a-week publication that covers local and state news and by ''All On Georgia - Douglas'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://douglas.allongeorgia.com/|title=Home - AllOnGeorgia|website=AllOnGeorgia}}</ref> a hyperlocal digital news organization that covers local, state and national news, daily. Chapel Hill News & Views also serves Douglasville as a monthly magazine with 45,000 circulation.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n* [[U.S. Highway 78]] ([[State Route 8 (Georgia)|State Route 8]], Veterans' Memorial Highway) runs directly east to west through downtown Douglasville.\n* [[Georgia State Route 92|State Route 92]] runs north to southeast just \u00bc of a mile to the east of downtown as a truck route designed to keep large trucks from crossing an elevated railroad crossing at Campbellton Street. The city and the Georgia DOT are working on plans to reroute Highway 92 farther east of downtown on a four-lane bridge serving as a bypass.\n* [[Georgia State Route 5|State Route 5]] is colocated with US 78 through downtown east to the [[Cobb County, Georgia|Cobb County]] line and west just past Hunter Park. Highway 5 continues in a southwesterly direction through the village of Bill Arp and crosses into [[Carroll County, Georgia|Carroll County]] near [[Whitesburg, Georgia|Whitesburg]].\n* [[Interstate 20]] (Ga Hwy 402) extends roughly east to west about {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} south of downtown, with access from Exits 34, 36, and 37.\n\nDouglasville is home to the single-runway [[Pinewood Airport]], located {{convert|5.7|mi|km}} northwest of downtown.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.airnav.com/airport/0GE0 |title=Pinewood Airport |publisher=Airnav.com |accessdate=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nResidents of Douglasville are served by the [[WellStar Douglas Hospital]] located at 8954 Hospital Drive; it has 98 licensed beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellstar.org/ws_content/ws_hospitals.aspx?id=394&pic_id=1326|title=Wellstar Douglas Hospital|access-date=November 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106082604/http://wellstar.org/ws_content/ws_hospitals.aspx?id=394&pic_id=1326|archive-date=November 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Douglasville Development Authority==\nThe primary goals of the City of Douglasville Development Authority (CDDA) are to promote the economic prosperity of the city while simultaneously increasing the existing industry and business sectors in order to raise the quality of life for the city's residents. The City Development Authority also focuses on education in order successfully promote the labor force.\n\nIn the fall of 2009, an area of interest for the CDDA was the reconstruction and widening of Highway 92, which runs through the heart of the city.<ref>{{cite web |title=Douglasville Highway 92 Project |year=2009 |url= http://www.gahwy92.com/ |publisher=Gagwy92.com}}</ref> This major roadway reconstruction was expected to have a significant impact on the city and its ability to promote economic development.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{alumni|residents|date=October 2019}}\n* [[Norma Jean (band)|Norma Jean]], Influential [[Metalcore]] band\n*[[Janie Lou Gibbs]], serial killer and poisoner died in a nursing home after being diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]] after being released from prison\n* [[Brian Heidik]], winner of ''[[Survivor: Thailand]]''\n* [[Lil Nas X]], rapper best known for the song \"[[Old Town Road]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}} <!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n* [http://www.douglasvillega.gov/ City of Douglasville official website]\n* [http://www.DouglasvilleDevelopment.com/ City of Douglasville Development Authority]\n* [http://www.visitdouglasville.com/ Douglasville Convention & Visitors Bureau]\n\n\n{{Atlanta Metro}}\n{{Douglas County, Georgia}}\n{{Historic Districts in Metro Atlanta}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Douglas County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:County seats in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1875]]\n[[Category:1875 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Chattahoochee River]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Atlanta metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox Settlement for other parameters or usage-->\n<!-- Basic info ----------------->\n| official_name            = Douglasville, Georgia\n| native_name              = <!--if native name is not in English-->\n| other_name               = \n| settlement_type          = [[City]]\n<!-- images and maps ------------>\n| image_skyline            = File:USA-Georgia-Douglasville County Courthouse.jpg\n| image_caption            = Douglas County 