{"title_page": "Ankur Vikal", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{Original research|date=June 2019}}\n{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2020}}}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n'''Ankur Vikal''' is an Indian film and theatre actor.\n\n==Early life==\n \nHe graduated from the [[National School of Drama]] (NSD), New Delhi in 2000, after studying Architecture at [[Maharaja Sayajirao University]] of [[Baroda]]. He has acted in the [[Motley (Theatre Group)|Motley Theatre Group]] in plays such as ''Manto Ismat Haazir Hain'', ''Safed Jhooth Kaali Shalwar'', ''Katha Kollage II'', ''All Thieves'','' The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'', and ''Salome''. His film career began with the Indian ground-breaking film ''[[Mango Souffl\u00e9]]'', followed by the highly acclaimed films ''[[Maqbool]]'' and ''Missed Call''.\n            \nAnkur played the role of Maman in ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008). It was nominated for 10 Academy Awards in 2009 and won 8- the most for any 2008 film-including Best Picture, Best Director, and Best adapted screenplay. It won 7 BAFTA awards including Best Film, 5 Critic's Choice Awards, and four Golden Globes. In the film, he discovers the children while they are living in the trash heaps and brings them to his Orphanage. He won a [[Screen Actor's Guild]] Award for his highly acclaimed and appreciated performance as Maman.\n\nHe also played the lead in ''[[The Forest (2009 film)|The Forest]]''. He was most recently seen in Telugu language film ''[[Kedi (2010 film)|Kedi]]'' and Hindi film ''[[Striker (2010 film)|Striker]]''.  In Tamil cinema he debuted in ''Mariyan'' (2013) where he played the role of an oil worker.\n\nHe played Yakub, the antagonist terrorist leader, in [[Anil Kapoor]]'s TV Series ''[[24 (Indian TV series)|24]]''.\n\nAnkur has been working and touring with [[Nirbhaya]] .The play has been called one of the most important pieces on Human Rights in the world. Ankur is the only male actor in it. He acts with 5 actresses sharing their personal stories of Sexual Abuse.  It has won the Fringe First Award, An Amnesty International and a Herald Angel when it opened in Edinburgh. It has been touring extensively in India, Europe and North America. A New York Times Critic's Pick, it is highly acclaimed and has been running successfully to full houses all over the world.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n*''[[Mango Souffl\u00e9]]'' (2002) as Kamlesh\n*''[[Maqbool]]'' (2003) as Riyaz Boti\n*''[[Missed Call (film)|Missed Call]]'' (2005) as Gaurav Sengupta \n*''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008) as Maman\n*''[[The Forest (2009 film)|The Forest]]'' (2009) as Pritam\n*''[[Striker (2010 film)|Striker]]'' (2010; Hindi) as Zaid\n*''[[Kedi (2010 film)|Kedi]]'' (2010; Telugu) as Chandra\n*\"[[Breaking the way]]\" (2010) as Ashok\n*''[[Maryan (film)|Maryan]]'' (2013; Tamil)\n*''[[Sold (2014 film)|Sold]]'' (2014) as Varun\n*''[[Bang Bang (2014 film)|Bang Bang]]'' (2014; Hindi) as Shoaib\n*''[[Blemished Light]]'' *2015) as Najib\n*''[[Jazbaa]]'' (2015; Hindi) as Vijay\n*''[[Phobia (2016 film)|Phobia]]'' (2016; Hindi) as Manu Malhotra\n*''[[Yaara]]'' (2016) as Fakira\n*''[[Indu Sarkar]]'' (2017; Hindi) as Shivam\n*''[[Mehandi Circus]]'' (2019; Tamil) as Jadhav\n\n===Television===\n*2013: ''[[24 (Indian TV series)|24]]'' as Yakub Sayeed\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1340178|Ankur Vikal}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vikal, Ankur}}\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda alumni]]\n\n{{India-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP IMDb only|date=June 2019}}\n{{Original research|date=June 2019}}\n{{BLP unsourced|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n'''Ankur Vikal''' is an Indian film and theatre actor.\n\n==Early life==\n \nHe graduated from the [[National School of Drama]] (NSD), New Delhi in 2000, after studying Architecture at [[Maharaja Sayajirao University]] of [[Baroda]]. He has acted in the [[Motley (Theatre Group)|Motley Theatre Group]] in plays such as ''Manto Ismat Haazir Hain'', ''Safed Jhooth Kaali Shalwar'', ''Katha Kollage II'', ''All Thieves'','' The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'', and ''Salome''. His film career began with the Indian ground-breaking film ''[[Mango Souffl\u00e9]]'', followed by the highly acclaimed films ''[[Maqbool]]'' and ''Missed Call''.\n            \nAnkur played the role of Maman in ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008). It was nominated for 10 Academy Awards in 2009 and won 8- the most for any 2008 film-including Best Picture, Best Director, and Best adapted screenplay. It won 7 BAFTA awards including Best Film, 5 Critic's Choice Awards, and four Golden Globes. In the film, he discovers the children while they are living in the trash heaps and brings them to his Orphanage. He won a [[Screen Actor's Guild]] Award for his highly acclaimed and appreciated performance as Maman.\n\nHe also played the lead in ''[[The Forest (2009 film)|The Forest]]''. He was most recently seen in Telugu language film ''[[Kedi (2010 film)|Kedi]]'' and Hindi film ''[[Striker (2010 film)|Striker]]''.  In Tamil cinema he debuted in ''Mariyan'' (2013) where he played the role of an oil worker.\n\nHe played Yakub, the antagonist terrorist leader, in [[Anil Kapoor]]'s TV Series ''[[24 (Indian TV series)|24]]''.\n\nAnkur has been working and touring with [[Nirbhaya]] .The play has been called one of the most important pieces on Human Rights in the world. Ankur is the only male actor in it. He acts with 5 actresses sharing their personal stories of Sexual Abuse.  It has won the Fringe First Award, An Amnesty International and a Herald Angel when it opened in Edinburgh. It has been touring extensively in India, Europe and North America. A New York Times Critic's Pick, it is highly acclaimed and has been running successfully to full houses all over the world.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n*''[[Mango Souffl\u00e9]]'' (2002) as Kamlesh\n*''[[Maqbool]]'' (2003) as Riyaz Boti\n*''[[Missed Call (film)|Missed Call]]'' (2005) as Gaurav Sengupta \n*''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008) as Maman\n*''[[The Forest (2009 film)|The Forest]]'' (2009) as Pritam\n*''[[Striker (2010 film)|Striker]]'' (2010; Hindi) as Zaid\n*''[[Kedi (2010 film)|Kedi]]'' (2010; Telugu) as Chandra\n*\"[[Breaking the way]]\" (2010) as Ashok\n*''[[Maryan (film)|Maryan]]'' (2013; Tamil)\n*''[[Sold (2014 film)|Sold]]'' (2014) as Varun\n*''[[Bang Bang (2014 film)|Bang Bang]]'' (2014; Hindi) as Shoaib\n*''[[Blemished Light]]'' *2015) as Najib\n*''[[Jazbaa]]'' (2015; Hindi) as Vijay\n*''[[Phobia (2016 film)|Phobia]]'' (2016; Hindi) as Manu Malhotra\n*''[[Yaara]]'' (2016) as Fakira\n*''[[Indu Sarkar]]'' (2017; Hindi) as Shivam\n*''[[Mehandi Circus]]'' (2019; Tamil) as Jadhav\n\n===Television===\n*2013: ''[[24 (Indian TV series)|24]]'' as Yakub Sayeed\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1340178|Ankur Vikal}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vikal, Ankur}}\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda alumni]]\n\n{{India-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ankur_Vikal"}
